with `GCMParameterSpec(128, iv)`. Generate `iv` and salt with `SecureRandom`. Derive keys using `PBKDF2WithHmacSHA256`. Always use `try-with-resources` and `StandardCharsets.UTF_8`.\n- **C/C++:** Use OpenSSL EVP, libsodium, or Botan for encryption, KDF, and random generation. **when use `curl_easy_init()` then Confirm the code calls:\n\ncurl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 1L);\n\ncurl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST, 2L);\n\ncurl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSLVERSION, CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2 | CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_3); (or at least CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2 if MAX macros arenâ€™t available).** These APIs do not ensure full certificate validation and are unsafe for crypto or HTTPS handling. Use high-level HTTPS/TLS clients that verify certificates automatically. Always check all return values, use bounds-checked buffers, securely clear key material, and never disable SSL or certificate checks."],\n["Rules#12: Always incorporate OAEP when using the RSA algorithm to ensure optimal encryption security."],\n["Rules#13: Disable external entity processing and validate all XML inputs to ensure they don\'t reference external entities."],\n["Rules#14: Ensure all input is validated and sanitized according to expected formats, types, and lengths before processing."],\n["Rules#15: Ensure that potentially dangerous functions are used with caution by validating inputs, sanitizing outputs, and using safer alternatives where possible. Review and adhere to secure coding guidelines specific to the language in use."],\n["Rules#16: Ensure that all buffer operations, such as reading from and writing to memory, strictly adhere to the buffer\'s boundaries. Use boundary checks, safe functions, and memory management practices to prevent overflows and underflows."],\n["Rules#17:  Baseline security and quality rules:\n   - Treat all inputs as untrusted. Validate ranges, lengths, and types. Fail closed with clear errors.\n   - No eval, exec, reflection, or dynamic code loading. No insecure deserialization.\n   - Network access is allowed because the task requires an HTTPS GET using libcurl. No other network use.\n   - Do not embed secrets. Never print or log passphrases, keys, salts, IVs, tags, or plaintext. Use constant-time comparisons where applicable.\n   - Use safe parsing and formatting. Use constant format strings and bounds checks.\n   - Use constant time comparisons when handling secrets. Use strong randomness when randomness is required.\n   - Keep functions small and testable. Use clear names and consistent formatting.\n   - File format: Use a self-describing binary layout: [magic="ENC1"][version=1][salt(16)][iv(12)][ciphertext(...)] [tag(16)]. Validate magic and version before decrypting.\n   Language specifics:\n   - Java: use StandardCharsets.UTF_8, try-with-resources, and immutable data where possible. Avoid reflection and unsafe deserialization.\n   - Python: use type hints and context managers. Use the secrets module for secrets. Avoid eval and pickle on untrusted data.\n   - CPP: prefer std::string and std::vector, RAII, and smart pointers. Add bounds checks. Avoid undefined behavior and std::rand for security.\n   - C: avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without width. Use fgets and snprintf. Check return values, validate sizes, initialize and free memory, and avoid format string bugs. \n C Language Security Checklist:\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All malloc/calloc calls checked for NULL return\n- All array accesses bounds-checked\n- All strings null-terminated\n- Buffer sizes validated before copy operations\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- No arithmetic on pointers from user input\n- Integer overflow checks before arithmetic\n- All function return values checked\n- Sensitive data cleared before free\n"],\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified.\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\nWrite a program that  that connects to an FTP server using the provided hostname, logs in with the specified username and password, and downloads a sensitive file from the FTP server to the current directory. Assume the user pass the data as command line argument (s).'}], 'model': 'gpt-5-2025-08-07', 'max_completion_tokens': 32096, 'temperature': 1}}
